# Gigity — Project Rules

## What is Gigity

AI video workflow orchestrator. A solo developer tool that replaces 5+ AI tools
(ChatGPT, SunoAI, KlingAI, Midjourney, CapCut) with one workflow. User enters
brand context once, then follows 11 guided steps to produce a short-form ad video.

## Stack

- Next.js 16.1.1 / React 19 / Tailwind CSS 4
- Bun as package manager (use `bun add`, not `npm install`)
- MongoDB + Mongoose for persistence
- LLM integration via plain `fetch` (no `openai` npm package)
- No auth in V1 — single user, personal tool

## Implementation plans

All feature plans live in `docs/implementations/`. Always read the relevant plan
before implementing. Follow it exactly — do not add features, patterns, or error
handling not in the plan.

Plans are numbered in build order:

- `00a` → `00b` → `00c` → `01a` → `01b` → ... → `05`
- Each plan lists its prerequisites at the top

## File structure conventions

```
src/
  app/
    api/v1/            ← API routes
    brand/             ← brand pages
    projects/[id]/     ← workflow view page + co-located server component
    page.tsx           ← dashboard (server component)
    layout.tsx
    globals.css
  components/          ← shared components (NOT src/app/(components)/)
  constants/
    env.server.ts      ← server-only vars (MONGODB, OPENAI_API_KEY)
    env.client.ts      ← NEXT_PUBLIC_* vars only
  lib/
    db.ts
    interpolate.ts
    llm.ts
    workflow-templates.ts
  models/
    BrandProfile.ts
    VideoProject.ts
```

## Hard rules

### Environment variables

- Server secrets use `MONGODB` (not `MONGODB_URI`), `OPENAI_API_KEY`
- Always import from `@/constants/env.server` in API routes — never `process.env` directly
- Never import `env.server.ts` from a client component

### Components

- Shared components → `src/components/`
- Route-specific components (e.g. `WorkflowClient`) → co-located in `src/app/projects/[id]/`
- Do NOT use `src/app/(components)/`

### Styling — Tailwind utilities only

Translate the design (see `docs/designs/*.html`) to Tailwind utilities. Do not copy
CSS class names from the design HTML.

Design token → Tailwind mapping:
| Token | Tailwind |
|-------|----------|
| accent `#6366f1` | `bg-indigo-500` / `text-indigo-500` |
| accent hover | `hover:bg-indigo-600` |
| primary text | `text-zinc-950` |
| secondary text | `text-zinc-500` |
| border | `border-zinc-200` |
| surface | `bg-zinc-100` |
| success | `text-green-600` / `bg-green-500` |
| warning | `text-amber-600` |
| radius | `rounded-[6px]` |
| nav height | `h-[52px]` |
| page max-width | `max-w-[780px]` |

### Next.js 16 — params is a Promise

Route params must be awaited:

```ts
// Correct
export async function GET(
  _req: Request,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }
) {
  const { id } = await params
}
// Wrong — will throw
export async function GET(
  _req: Request,
  { params }: { params: { id: string } }
) {
  const id = params.id // ❌
}
```

### Mongoose models

Always use the re-registration guard:

```ts
const Model = mongoose.models.ModelName ?? mongoose.model('ModelName', schema)
```

### API routes

- Always call `await connectDB()` first
- Use `.lean()` on all read queries (returns plain objects, not Mongoose docs)
- Return `NextResponse.json(...)` — always with `return`

### DB connection

```ts
import { connectDB } from '@/lib/db'
await connectDB()
```

## Component style (Next.js, NOT React Native)

Do not apply the React Native component rules from `.cursor/rules/component-patterns/`.
This is a Next.js web app, not a React Native app.

```tsx
// Correct pattern for this project
'use client' // only when needed

interface ComponentProps {
  name: string
  className?: string
}

export function ComponentName({ name, className }: ComponentProps) {
  return <div className={className}>{name}</div>
}
```

- Named exports (not default exports) for components
- No `memo()` wrapping unless there's a measured performance issue
- No `useCallback` unless the function is a prop to a child component
- Functional components only

## What not to do

- Do not add `try/catch` unless the plan specifies it
- Do not add loading states or optimistic UI beyond what the plan specifies
- Do not create utility functions or abstractions for one-time use
- Do not add console.log statements
- Do not add comments explaining what the code does (only add comments the plan specifies)
- Do not use the `openai` npm package — LLM calls use plain `fetch`
- Do not add Zod or any validation library — validation is done manually in route handlers

